Habermas makes the point that in the past people acquired societal "dignity" through their belonging to the hereditary aristocracy or participation in university student corporations or trade guilds - the Guenon reader will note the initiatory character of all of the named above.

Evola pointed out students and aristocrats were the only groups allowed to participate in legal duels - thus human dignity rests on your capacity to risk your life over honor. Or it used to. Now it's somehow in the constitution. No idea how that happened. Habermas talks about it.
